Exercise 07 - Fireflies

Learning objectives

  • Understand the difference between forward and deferred rendering.
  • Visualize the contents of the different g-buffers.
  • Learn how to pack and unpack data from the g-buffers.

Remember that you can find hints in comments in the code, tagged with the label "(todo)" followed by the number of the exercise.

Exercise 07.0 - Forward rendering (live coding)

In this exercise the teacher will give a quick overview of the new renderer and finalize the implementation of the forward rendering pass.

Exercise 07.1 - Distance attenuation

In reality, light intensity attenuates inversely proportional to the square of the distance. For now we will ignore that part, but we need to define some radius to delimit the distance of the point and spot lights.

For simplicity, we will use GLSL function smoothstep. This function takes two values as a range (min, max) and a third value to sample in that range. At min, the function returns 0. At max, the function returns 1. In between, it smoothly interpolates from 0 to 1 depending on the position in that range. Notice that, despite the name, min does not have to be larger than max.

The attenuation range can be set in the light object, and is already being passed to the shader in the uniform LightAttenuation. This uniform stores the range for distance attenuation in XY and the angle attenuation (out of scope) in ZW.

Your job is to finish the implementation on the shader side:

  1. In C++, locate where the point light object is being created and assign some attenuation values.
  2. You can use fixed distances, or random values (within a reasonable range) or customize it in runtime by adding controls to ImGui.
  3. In the shader, find where the common lighting code is located. Follow the logic and find where the distance attenuation is computed.
  4. Replace the current implementation (1 = no attenuation) with a smoothstep using the range you just provided. Read carefully how smoothstep works, to write the parameters in the correct order. For the third parameter, use the distance to the light.

Once it is implemented, adjust visually the attenuation range to something reasonable (not too large).

Exercise 07.2 - Albedo g-buffer

We can start now with deferred rendering. As mentioned during the lecture, it is split in 2 passes. The first pass renders the geometry data to textures, the second one reads from those textures and applies the lighting.

Most of the setup has been done for you, to simplify the exercise, but feel free to look at the implementation and ask if there is anything you don't understand.

Before computing the lighting information, we will go one by one storing the data in the g-buffers.

We will start with albedo first:

  1. First of all, change the render mode from forward to deferred in the constructor of the fireflies application. This variable is there to be able to compare both modes at the end, but it is not possible to change in runtime.
  2. The g-buffers need to be stored in the framebuffer used by the GBufferRenderPass. Set the albedo texture as a Draw target, assigned to attachment Color0. Look at the existing example with depth, for inspiration.
  3. In the same class, look for the creation of the texture, and initialize it with SetImage, with the size provided, using RGBA as format and RGBA8 as internal format.
  4. We will always read and write to these textures with a pixel ratio 1:1, so we will disable the linear interpolation in the minification and magnification parameters, by setting it to nearest. You can find these two parameters as TextureObject::ParameterEnum.
  5. In the gbuffer fragment shader, we need to write the value to the albedo output (currently 0). The value stored here is the Color uniform multiplied by the color texture, in the same way that it is done in the lit fragment shader. The alpha is not used, you can store any value.
  6. Finally, in the deferred fragment shader, read the value from the albedo texture and set it as the fragment output.

Now you will see the objects with no lighting, just the plain color. If you add more and more fireflies, it will turn brighter due to the additive passes.

Exercise 07.3 - Normal g-buffer

The next g-buffer we are going to fill is the one storing the normals.

Repeat the steps you did before, with some differences:

  1. Normal g-buffer uses attachment Color1.
  2. The format for normal g-buffer is RG, with internal format RG16F. This means that we only store 2 components (16 bit floats each) and will reconstruct the third one, as seen during the lecture.
  3. In the gbuffer fragment shader, you can store the view normal input directly (only X and Y components).
  4. The deferred fragment, however, is more complicated. We will use a helper function, GetImplicitNormal, to get the third component. You can find the function in our utils.glsl file, but you need to implement it, and then assign the result to FragColor. Don't hesitate to go back to the slides for the formula, if you need to.

Take some time to observe the colors from the normal and try to estimate their value.

Exercise 07.4 - Reconstructing the position from depth g-buffer

For the depth buffer, we needed it for everything else to work properly, so part of it was already configured.

However, there are a couple things to do:

  1. When initializing the depth texture, set the minification and magnification parameters to nearest, as we did with the others.
  2. In the deferred fragment shader, the depth buffer is available to read as a texture. We can use it to extract the original position of every fragment. We will use another helper function in utils.glsl, ReconstructViewPosition, and you will have to implement it this time as well. Follow these steps:
    • Read the depth value from the depth texture, using the texture coordinates. It will be stored in the first channel.
    • The value from the texture is normalized to the range (0, 1), you need to renormalize it to (-1, 1). This will be the Z component of our clip space coordinates.
    • For the X and Y, we can use the texture coordinates. In this case we have to do the same normalization, because the NDC coordinates are in the range (-1, 1).
    • Now that we have the position in clip space, we can transform it to view space, multiplying by the inverse of the projection matrix, which is available as a uniform.
    • Finally, divide the result of the transformation by the W component (it should be a vec4), and return the XYZ.
  3. Assign the position value to the fragment output temporarily, to validate the result.

How do these colors compare to the normals?

Exercise 07.5 - Lighting

The last g-buffer is quite trivial, after doing the others, so we will do the lighting at the same time.

Repeat the steps once more, packing in the gbuffer fragment shader the reflectance values together in the RGB components.

For the specular value, you will have to transform it to a range (0, 1). I suggest storing
w = 1 / (1 + exponent)
and doing the inverse operation when reading it in the deferred fragment shader.

Now that we have everything we need in the deferred fragment shader, we can proceed to compute the lighting.

One important note is that we will do the lighting in world space, to reuse all the lighting uniforms. The lecture suggests that sometimes it is more convenient to use view space, but it won't be the case this time.

Final steps to get the lighting:

  1. Create a structure SurfaceData, similar to the one used in lit fragment shader.
  2. Fill it in with all the information that we have been recovering from the g-buffers.
  3. Be careful with the normal. The value stored in the texture is in view space, we need to transform it to world space, multiplying by the inverse view matrix.
  4. Reconstruct the position from depth, as seen in the previous exercise. This position is in view space as well. You can take advantage of this and the fact that the position of the camera is 0 in view space, to compute easily the view vector (in view space).
  5. Transform the position and the view vector to world coordinates, as you did with the normal. Be careful, for the position, the 4th component should be one; for the normal and the view vector, it should be 0.
  6. Finally, invoke the ComputeLighting function, and assign the value to the FragColor.

Congratulations! You have a functional deferred renderer!

Exercise 07.X - Get creative (optional)

The renderer we are using is too simple, and there are multiple options to improve it:

  • Use different geometry to render additional lights, instead of fullscreen passes. A simple option would be a cube with the side of the radius.
  • Change the texture of the firefly abdomen with one that has alpha, and pack that alpha in the free channel in albedo alpha. Later on, you can use that intensity to add emissive color, multiplied with the albedo.
  • Add a simple shadow map pass, using the Renderer structure.
